{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_47a7cd22e2df42ccb6195b77","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t.. _devenv:\n2\t\n3\t***********************\n4\tDevelopment environment\n5\t***********************\n6\t\n7\tThis page describes a common development setup for working with Mopidy and\n8\tMopidy extensions. Of course, there may be other ways that work better for you\n9\tand the tools you use, but here's one recommended way to do it.\n10\t\n11\t.. contents::\n12\t   :local:\n13\t\n14\t\n15\tInitial setup\n16\t=============\n17\t\n18\tThe following steps help you get a good initial setup. They build on each other\n19\tto some degree, so if you're not very familiar with Python development it might\n20\tbe wise to proceed in the order laid out here.\n21\t\n22\t.. contents::\n23\t   :local:\n24\t\n25\t\n26\tInstall Mopidy the regular way\n27\t------------------------------\n28\t\n29\tInstall Mopidy the regular way. Mopidy has some non-Python dependencies which\n30\tmay be tricky to install. Thus we recommend to always start with a full regular\n31\tMopidy install, as described in :ref:`installation`. That is, if you're running\n32\te.g. Debian, start with installing Mopidy from Debian packages.\n33\t\n34\t\n35\tMake a development workspace\n36\t----------------------------\n37\t\n38\tMake a directory to be used as a workspace for all your Mopidy development::\n39\t\n40\t    mkdir ~/mopidy-dev\n41\t\n42\tIt will contain all the Git repositories you'll check out when working on\n43\tMopidy and extensions.\n44\t\n45\t\n46\tMake a virtualenv\n47\t-----------------\n48\t\n49\tMake a Python virtualenv for Mopidy development.\n50\tThe virtualenv will wall off Mopidy and its dependencies from the rest of your system.\n51\tAll development and installation of Python dependencies,\n52\tversions of Mopidy, and extensions are done inside the virtualenv.\n53\tThis way your regular Mopidy install,\n54\twhich you set up in the first step,\n55\tis unaffected by your hacking and will always be working.\n56\t\n57\tTo create a virtualenv in the Mopidy workspace directory, run::\n58\t\n59\t    python3 -m venv ~/mopidy-dev/.venv\n60\t\n61\tNow, each time you open a terminal and want to activate the ``mopidy``\n62\tvirtualenv, run::\n63\t\n64\t    . ~/mopidy-dev/.venv/bin/activate\n65\t\n66\tThere are lots of ways to set up your shell to automatically activate the virtualenv,\n67\te.g. when changing directory into ``~/mopidy-dev/`` or a subdirectory.\n68\tAs this is just convenience and not strictly required,\n69\tit is left as an exercise for the reader.\n70\t\n71\t\n72\tClone the repo from GitHub\n73\t--------------------------\n74\t\n75\tOnce inside the virtualenv, it's time to clone the ``mopidy/mopidy`` Git repo\n76\tfrom GitHub::\n77\t\n78\t    cd ~/mopidy-dev/\n79\t    git clone https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git\n80\t\n81\tWhen you've cloned the ``mopidy`` Git repo, ``cd`` into it::\n82\t\n83\t    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/\n84\t\n85\tWith a fresh clone of the Git repo, you should start out on the ``main``\n86\tbranch. This is where all features for the next feature release land. To\n87\tconfirm that you're on the right branch, run::\n88\t\n89\t    git branch\n90\t\n91\t\n92\tInstall Mopidy from the Git repo\n93\t--------------------------------\n94\t\n95\tNext up, we'll want to run Mopidy from the Git repo. There's two reasons for\n96\tthis: first of all, it lets you easily change the source code, restart Mopidy,\n97\tand see the change take effect. Second, it's a convenient way to keep at the\n98\tbleeding edge, testing the latest developments in Mopidy itself or test some\n99\textension against the latest Mopidy changes.\n100\t\n101\tAssuming you're still inside the Git repo, use pip to install Mopidy from the\n102\tGit repo in an \"editable\" form::\n103\t\n104\t    pip install --upgrade --editable .\n105\t\n106\tWhen using the ``--editable`` flag, the source code is not copied into the\n107\tvirtualenv's ``site-packages`` directory, but instead creates a link there\n108\tpointing to the Git repo. This way, you can change the source code in the Git\n109\trepo and the changes will be visible inside the virtualenv without having to\n110\treinstall Mopidy.\n111\t\n112\tIt will also create a ``mopidy`` executable inside the virtualenv that will\n113\talways run the latest code from the Git repo::\n114\t\n115\t    $ cat ~/mopidy-dev/.venv/bin/mopidy\n116\t    ...\n117\t\n118\tThis file is on the path when the virtualenv is active, so you can run it from\n119\tanywhere, simply by running::\n120\t\n121\t    mopidy\n122\t\n123\t.. note::\n124\t\n125\t    It is also possible to run Python apps directly,\n126\t    e.g. using ``python3 src/mopidy`` directly on the\n127\t    :file:`~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/src/mopidy/` Python package directory.\n128\t    However, if you don't run the install command above,\n129\t    the extensions bundled with Mopidy will not be registered and made available\n130\t    for use, making Mopidy quite useless.\n131\t\n132\tThird, the install command will register the bundled Mopidy\n133\textensions so that Mopidy may find them through :mod:`importlib`.\n134\tThe result of this can be seen in a file named :file:`entry_points.txt`\n135\twhich can be found inside the virtualenv dir, e.g.\n136\t:file:`~/mopidy-dev/.venv/lib/python3.11/site-packages/Mopidy-4.0.0.dist-info/entry_points.txt`.\n137\tThe :file:`entry_points.txt` file is of special interest as it shows both how\n138\tthe above executable and the bundled extensions are connected to the Mopidy\n139\tsource code:\n140\t\n141\t.. code-block:: ini\n142\t\n143\t    [console_scripts]\n144\t    mopidy = mopidy.__main__:main\n145\t\n146\t    [mopidy.ext]\n147\t    file = mopidy.file:Extension\n148\t    http = mopidy.http:Extension\n149\t    m3u = mopidy.m3u:Extension\n150\t    softwaremixer = mopidy.softwaremixer:Extension\n151\t    stream = mopidy.stream:Extension\n152\t\n153\t\n154\tInstall development tools\n155\t-------------------------\n156\t\n157\tBefore continuing, you will probably want to install the development tools we\n158\tuse as well. These can be installed into the active virtualenv by running::\n159\t\n160\t    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/\n161\t    pip install --upgrade --editable \".[dev]\"\n162\t\n163\tNote that this is the same command as you used to install Mopidy from the Git\n164\trepo, with the addition of the ``[dev]`` suffix after ``.``. This makes pip\n165\tinstall the \"dev\" set of extra dependencies. Exactly what the \"dev\" set\n166\tincludes are defined in :file:`pyproject.toml`. Since pip v25.1 you can\n167\tinstead do::\n168\t\n169\t    pip install --upgrade --group dev --editable .\n170\t\n171\tTo upgrade the development tools in the future, just rerun the exact same\n172\tcommand.\n173\t\n174\t\n175\t.. _running-from-git:\n176\t\n177\tRunning Mopidy from Git\n178\t=======================\n179\t\n180\tAs long as the virtualenv is activated, you can start Mopidy from any\n181\tdirectory. Simply run::\n182\t\n183\t    mopidy\n184\t\n185\tTo stop it again, press :kbd:`Ctrl+C`.\n186\t\n187\tEvery time you change code in Mopidy or an extension and want to see it\n188\tlive, you must restart Mopidy.\n189\t\n190\tIf you want to iterate quickly while developing, it may sound a bit tedious to\n191\trestart Mopidy for every minor change. Then it's useful to have tests to\n192\texercise your code...\n193\t\n194\t\n195\t.. _running-tests:\n196\t\n197\tRunning tests\n198\t=============\n199\t\n200\tMopidy has quite good test coverage, and we would like all new code going into\n201\tMopidy to come with tests.\n202\t\n203\t.. contents::\n204\t   :local:\n205\t\n206\t\n207\tTest it all\n208\t-----------\n209\t\n210\tYou need to know at least one command; the one that runs all the tests::\n211\t\n212\t    tox\n213\t\n214\tThis will run exactly the same tests as our CI setup runs for all our\n215\tbranches and pull requests. If this command turns green, you can be quite\n216\tconfident that your pull request will get the green flag from CI as well,\n217\twhich is a requirement for it to be merged.\n218\t\n219\tAs this is the ultimate test command, it's also the one taking the most time to\n220\trun; up to a minute, depending on your system. But, if you have patience, this\n221\tis all you need to know. Always run this command before pushing your changes to\n222\tGitHub.\n223\t\n224\tIf you take a look at the tox config file, :file:`tox.ini`, you'll see that tox\n225\truns tests in multiple environments, including a ``ruff`` environment that\n226\tlints the source code for issues and a ``docs`` environment that tests that the\n227\tdocumentation can be built. You can also limit tox to just test specific\n228\tenvironments using the ``-e`` option, e.g. to run just unit tests on Python 3.11::\n229\t\n230\t    tox -e py311\n231\t\n232\tTo learn more, see the `tox documentation <https://tox.readthedocs.io/>`_ .\n233\t\n234\tBefore submitting a pull request, we recommend running::\n235\t\n236\t    tox\n237\t\n238\tThis will locally run similar tests to what we use in our CI runs and help us to\n239\tmerge high-quality contributions.\n240\t\n241\t\n242\tRunning unit tests\n243\t------------------\n244\t\n245\tUnder the hood, ``tox -e py311`` will use `pytest <https://docs.pytest.org/>`_\n246\tas the test runner. We can also use it directly to run all tests::\n247\t\n248\t    pytest\n249\t\n250\tpytest has lots of possibilities, so you'll have to dive into their docs and\n251\tplugins to get full benefit from it. To get you interested, here are some\n252\texamples.\n253\t\n254\tWe can limit to just tests in a single directory to save time::\n255\t\n256\t    pytest tests/http/\n257\t\n258\tWith the help of the ``pytest-xdist`` plugin, we can run tests with four Python\n259\tprocesses in parallel, which usually cuts the test time in half or more::\n260\t\n261\t    pytest -n 4\n262\t\n263\tAnother useful feature from ``pytest-xdist``, is the possibility to stop on the\n264\tfirst test failure, watch the file system for changes, and then rerun the\n265\ttests. This makes for a very quick code-test cycle::\n266\t\n267\t    pytest -f    # or --looponfail\n268\t\n269\tWith the help of the pytest-cov plugin, we can get a report on what parts of\n270\tthe given module are covered by the test suite::\n271\t\n272\t    pytest --cov\n273\t\n274\t.. note::\n275\t\n276\t    Up to date test coverage statistics can also be viewed online at\n277\t    `Codecov <https://codecov.io/gh/mopidy/mopidy>`_.\n278\t\n279\tIf we want to speed up the test suite, we can even get a list of the ten\n280\tslowest tests::\n281\t\n282\t    pytest --durations=10\n283\t\n284\tBy now, you should be convinced that running pytest directly during\n285\tdevelopment can be very useful.\n286\t\n287\t\n288\tContinuous integration\n289\t----------------------\n290\t\n291\tMopidy uses `GitHub Actions <https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy/actions>`_ for\n292\tautomatically running the test suite when code is pushed to GitHub. This\n293\tworks both for the main Mopidy repo, but also for any forks. This way, any\n294\tcontributions to Mopidy through GitHub will automatically be tested, and the\n295\tbuild status will be visible in the GitHub pull request interface, making it\n296\teasier to evaluate the quality of pull requests.\n297\t\n298\tFor each successful build, the CI setup submits code coverage data to\n299\t`Codecov`_. If you're out of work, Codecov might help you find areas in the\n300\tcode which could need better test coverage.\n301\t\n302\t\n303\t.. _code-linting:\n304\t\n305\tStyle checking and linting\n306\t--------------------------\n307\t\n308\tWe're quite pedantic about :ref:`codestyle` and try hard to keep the Mopidy\n309\tcode base a very clean and nice place to work in.\n310\t\n311\tLuckily, you can get very far by using the `ruff\n312\t<https://github.com/astral-sh/ruff>`_ linter to check your code for issues before\n313\tsubmitting a pull request. Mopidy's ruff rules are configured in :file:`pyproject.toml`.\n314\tYou can either run the ``ruff`` tox environment, like our CI setup will do on\n315\tyour pull request::\n316\t\n317\t    tox -e ruff\n318\t\n319\tOr you can run ruff directly::\n320\t\n321\t    ruff .\n322\t\n323\tIf successful, the command will not print anything at all.\n324\t\n325\t.. note::\n326\t\n327\t    In some rare cases it doesn't make sense to listen to ruff's warnings. In\n328\t    those cases, ignore the check by appending ``# noqa: <warning code>`` to\n329\t    the source line that triggers the warning. The ``# noqa`` part will make\n330\t    ruff skip all checks on the line, while the warning code will help other\n331\t    developers lookup what you are ignoring.\n332\t\n333\t\n334\t.. _writing-docs:\n335\t\n336\tWriting documentation\n337\t=====================\n338\t\n339\tTo write documentation, we use `Sphinx <https://www.sphinx-doc.org/>`_. See\n340\ttheir site for lots of documentation on how to use Sphinx.\n341\t\n342\t.. note::\n343\t\n344\t    To generate a few graphs which are part of the documentation, you need to\n345\t    install the graphviz package. You can install it from APT with::\n346\t\n347\t        sudo apt install graphviz\n348\t\n349\t    Other distributions typically use the same package name.\n350\t\n351\tTo build the documentation, go into the :file:`docs/` directory::\n352\t\n353\t    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/docs/\n354\t\n355\tThen, to see all available build targets, run::\n356\t\n357\t    make\n358\t\n359\tTo generate an HTML version of the documentation, run::\n360\t\n361\t    make html\n362\t\n363\tThe generated HTML will be available at :file:`_build/html/index.html`. To open\n364\tit in a browser you can run either of the following commands, depending on your\n365\tOS::\n366\t\n367\t    xdg-open _build/html/index.html    # Linux\n368\t    open _build/html/index.html        # OS X\n369\t\n370\tThe documentation at https://docs.mopidy.com/ is hosted by `Read the Docs\n371\t<https://readthedocs.org/>`_, which automatically updates the documentation\n372\twhen a change is pushed to the ``mopidy/mopidy`` repo at GitHub.\n373\t\n374\t\n375\tWorking on extensions\n376\t=====================\n377\t\n378\tMuch of the above also applies to Mopidy extensions, though they're often a bit\n379\tsimpler. They don't have documentation sites and their test suites are either\n380\tsmall and fast, or sadly missing entirely. Most of them use tox to run various\n381\tlinters, and pytest can be used to run their test suites.\n382\t\n383\t.. contents::\n384\t   :local:\n385\t\n386\t\n387\tInstalling extensions\n388\t---------------------\n389\t\n390\tAs always, the ``mopidy`` virtualenv should be active when working on\n391\textensions::\n392\t\n393\t    . ~/mopidy-dev/.venv/bin/activate\n394\t\n395\tJust like with non-development Mopidy installations, you can install extensions\n396\tusing pip::\n397\t\n398\t    pip install Mopidy-Scrobbler\n399\t\n400\tInstalling an extension from its Git repo works the same way as with Mopidy\n401\titself. First, go to the Mopidy workspace::\n402\t\n403\t    cd ~/mopidy-dev/\n404\t\n405\tClone the desired Mopidy extension::\n406\t\n407\t    git clone https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy-spotify.git\n408\t\n409\tChange to the newly created extension directory::\n410\t\n411\t    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy-spotify/\n412\t\n413\tThen, install the extension in \"editable\" mode, so that it can be imported from\n414\tanywhere inside the virtualenv and the extension is registered and discoverable\n415\tthrough :mod:`importlib`::\n416\t\n417\t    pip install --editable .\n418\t\n419\tEvery extension will have a ``README.rst`` file. It may contain information\n420\tabout extra dependencies required, development process, etc. Extensions usually\n421\thave a changelog in their GitHub releases page.\n422\t\n423\t\n424\tUpgrading extensions\n425\t--------------------\n426\t\n427\tExtensions often have a much quicker life cycle than Mopidy itself, often with\n428\tdaily releases in periods of active development. To find outdated extensions in\n429\tyour virtualenv, you can run::\n430\t\n431\t    pip list --outdated\n432\t\n433\tTo upgrade an extension installed with pip, simply use pip::\n434\t\n435\t    pip install --upgrade Mopidy-Scrobbler\n436\t\n437\tTo upgrade an extension installed from a Git repo, it's usually enough to pull\n438\tthe new changes in::\n439\t\n440\t    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy-spotify/\n441\t    git pull\n442\t\n443\tOf course, if you have local modifications, you'll need to stash these away on\n444\ta branch or similar first.\n445\t\n446\tDepending on the changes to the extension, it may be necessary to update the\n447\tmetadata about the extension package by installing it in \"editable\" mode\n448\tagain::\n449\t\n450\t    pip install --editable .\n451\t\n452\t\n453\tContribution workflow\n454\t=====================\n455\t\n456\tBefore you being, make sure you've read the :ref:`contributing` page and the\n457\tguidelines there. This section will focus more on the practical workflow.\n458\t\n459\tFor the examples, we're making a change to Mopidy. Approximately the same\n460\tworkflow should work for most Mopidy extensions too.\n461\t\n462\t.. contents::\n463\t   :local:\n464\t\n465\t\n466\tSetting up Git remotes\n467\t----------------------\n468\t\n469\tAssuming we already have a local Git clone of the upstream Git repo in\n470\t:file:`~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/`, we can run ``git remote -v`` to list the\n471\tconfigured remotes of the repo::\n472\t\n473\t    $ git remote -v\n474\t    origin  https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (fetch)\n475\t    origin  https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (push)\n476\t\n477\tFor clarity, we can rename the ``origin`` remote to ``upstream``::\n478\t\n479\t    $ git remote rename origin upstream\n480\t    $ git remote -v\n481\t    upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (fetch)\n482\t    upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (push)\n483\t\n484\tIf you haven't already, `fork the repository\n485\t<https://help.github.com/en/articles/fork-a-repo>`_ to your own GitHub account.\n486\t\n487\tThen, add the new fork as a remote to your local clone::\n488\t\n489\t    git remote add myuser git@github.com:myuser/mopidy.git\n490\t\n491\tThe end result is that you have both the upstream repo and your own fork as\n492\tremotes::\n493\t\n494\t    $ git remote -v\n495\t    myuser  git@github.com:myuser/mopidy.git (fetch)\n496\t    myuser  git@github.com:myuser/mopidy.git (push)\n497\t    upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (fetch)\n498\t    upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (push)\n499\t\n500\t\n501\tCreating a branch\n502\t-----------------\n503\t\n504\tFetch the latest data from all remotes without affecting your working\n505\tdirectory::\n506\t\n507\t    git remote update --prune\n508\t\n509\tNow, we are ready to create and checkout a new branch off of the upstream\n510\t``main`` branch for our work::\n511\t\n512\t    git checkout -b fix-crash-on-foo upstream/main\n513\t\n514\tDo the work, while remembering to adhere to code style, test the changes, make\n515\tnecessary updates to the documentation, and making small commits with good\n516\tcommit messages. All as described in :ref:`contributing` and elsewhere in\n517\tthe :ref:`devenv` guide.\n518\t\n519\t\n520\tCreating a pull request\n521\t-----------------------\n522\t\n523\tWhen everything is done and committed, push the branch to your fork on GitHub::\n524\t\n525\t    git push myuser fix-crash-on-foo\n526\t\n527\tGo to the repository on GitHub where you want the change merged, in this case\n528\thttps://github.com/mopidy/mopidy, and `create a pull request\n529\t<https://help.github.com/en/articles/creating-a-pull-request>`_.\n530\t\n531\t\n532\tUpdating a pull request\n533\t-----------------------\n534\t\n535\tWhen the pull request is created, our CI setup will run all tests on it.\n536\tIf something fails, you'll usually get a notification from GitHub.\n537\tYou might as well just fix the issues right away,\n538\tas we won't merge a pull request without all CI builds being green.\n539\tSee :ref:`running-tests` on how to run the same tests locally as\n540\tour CI setup runs on your pull request.\n541\t\n542\tWhen you've fixed the issues, you can update the pull request simply by pushing\n543\tmore commits to the same branch in your fork::\n544\t\n545\t    git push myuser fix-crash-on-foo\n546\t\n547\tLikewise, when you get review comments from other developers on your pull\n548\trequest, you're expected to create additional commits which addresses the\n549\tcomments. Push them to your branch so that the pull request is updated.\n550\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"103cb0b3-2c64-4af6-9698-f7dcc320b7b5","uuid":"a8879f86-8e96-4fd8-a7da-ac66a4fd2eae","timestamp":"2026-04-06T10:35:34.167Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/devenv.rst","content":".. _devenv:\n\n***********************\nDevelopment environment\n***********************\n\nThis page describes a common development setup for working with Mopidy and\nMopidy extensions. Of course, there may be other ways that work better for you\nand the tools you use, but here's one recommended way to do it.\n\n.. contents::\n   :local:\n\n\nInitial setup\n=============\n\nThe following steps help you get a good initial setup. They build on each other\nto some degree, so if you're not very familiar with Python development it might\nbe wise to proceed in the order laid out here.\n\n.. contents::\n   :local:\n\n\nInstall Mopidy the regular way\n------------------------------\n\nInstall Mopidy the regular way. Mopidy has some non-Python dependencies which\nmay be tricky to install. Thus we recommend to always start with a full regular\nMopidy install, as described in :ref:`installation`. That is, if you're running\ne.g. Debian, start with installing Mopidy from Debian packages.\n\n\nMake a development workspace\n----------------------------\n\nMake a directory to be used as a workspace for all your Mopidy development::\n\n    mkdir ~/mopidy-dev\n\nIt will contain all the Git repositories you'll check out when working on\nMopidy and extensions.\n\n\nMake a virtualenv\n-----------------\n\nMake a Python virtualenv for Mopidy development.\nThe virtualenv will wall off Mopidy and its dependencies from the rest of your system.\nAll development and installation of Python dependencies,\nversions of Mopidy, and extensions are done inside the virtualenv.\nThis way your regular Mopidy install,\nwhich you set up in the first step,\nis unaffected by your hacking and will always be working.\n\nTo create a virtualenv in the Mopidy workspace directory, run::\n\n    python3 -m venv ~/mopidy-dev/.venv\n\nNow, each time you open a terminal and want to activate the ``mopidy``\nvirtualenv, run::\n\n    . ~/mopidy-dev/.venv/bin/activate\n\nThere are lots of ways to set up your shell to automatically activate the virtualenv,\ne.g. when changing directory into ``~/mopidy-dev/`` or a subdirectory.\nAs this is just convenience and not strictly required,\nit is left as an exercise for the reader.\n\n\nClone the repo from GitHub\n--------------------------\n\nOnce inside the virtualenv, it's time to clone the ``mopidy/mopidy`` Git repo\nfrom GitHub::\n\n    cd ~/mopidy-dev/\n    git clone https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git\n\nWhen you've cloned the ``mopidy`` Git repo, ``cd`` into it::\n\n    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/\n\nWith a fresh clone of the Git repo, you should start out on the ``main``\nbranch. This is where all features for the next feature release land. To\nconfirm that you're on the right branch, run::\n\n    git branch\n\n\nInstall Mopidy from the Git repo\n--------------------------------\n\nNext up, we'll want to run Mopidy from the Git repo. There's two reasons for\nthis: first of all, it lets you easily change the source code, restart Mopidy,\nand see the change take effect. Second, it's a convenient way to keep at the\nbleeding edge, testing the latest developments in Mopidy itself or test some\nextension against the latest Mopidy changes.\n\nAssuming you're still inside the Git repo, use pip to install Mopidy from the\nGit repo in an \"editable\" form::\n\n    pip install --upgrade --editable .\n\nWhen using the ``--editable`` flag, the source code is not copied into the\nvirtualenv's ``site-packages`` directory, but instead creates a link there\npointing to the Git repo. This way, you can change the source code in the Git\nrepo and the changes will be visible inside the virtualenv without having to\nreinstall Mopidy.\n\nIt will also create a ``mopidy`` executable inside the virtualenv that will\nalways run the latest code from the Git repo::\n\n    $ cat ~/mopidy-dev/.venv/bin/mopidy\n    ...\n\nThis file is on the path when the virtualenv is active, so you can run it from\nanywhere, simply by running::\n\n    mopidy\n\n.. note::\n\n    It is also possible to run Python apps directly,\n    e.g. using ``python3 src/mopidy`` directly on the\n    :file:`~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/src/mopidy/` Python package directory.\n    However, if you don't run the install command above,\n    the extensions bundled with Mopidy will not be registered and made available\n    for use, making Mopidy quite useless.\n\nThird, the install command will register the bundled Mopidy\nextensions so that Mopidy may find them through :mod:`importlib`.\nThe result of this can be seen in a file named :file:`entry_points.txt`\nwhich can be found inside the virtualenv dir, e.g.\n:file:`~/mopidy-dev/.venv/lib/python3.11/site-packages/Mopidy-4.0.0.dist-info/entry_points.txt`.\nThe :file:`entry_points.txt` file is of special interest as it shows both how\nthe above executable and the bundled extensions are connected to the Mopidy\nsource code:\n\n.. code-block:: ini\n\n    [console_scripts]\n    mopidy = mopidy.__main__:main\n\n    [mopidy.ext]\n    file = mopidy.file:Extension\n    http = mopidy.http:Extension\n    m3u = mopidy.m3u:Extension\n    softwaremixer = mopidy.softwaremixer:Extension\n    stream = mopidy.stream:Extension\n\n\nInstall development tools\n-------------------------\n\nBefore continuing, you will probably want to install the development tools we\nuse as well. These can be installed into the active virtualenv by running::\n\n    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/\n    pip install --upgrade --editable \".[dev]\"\n\nNote that this is the same command as you used to install Mopidy from the Git\nrepo, with the addition of the ``[dev]`` suffix after ``.``. This makes pip\ninstall the \"dev\" set of extra dependencies. Exactly what the \"dev\" set\nincludes are defined in :file:`pyproject.toml`. Since pip v25.1 you can\ninstead do::\n\n    pip install --upgrade --group dev --editable .\n\nTo upgrade the development tools in the future, just rerun the exact same\ncommand.\n\n\n.. _running-from-git:\n\nRunning Mopidy from Git\n=======================\n\nAs long as the virtualenv is activated, you can start Mopidy from any\ndirectory. Simply run::\n\n    mopidy\n\nTo stop it again, press :kbd:`Ctrl+C`.\n\nEvery time you change code in Mopidy or an extension and want to see it\nlive, you must restart Mopidy.\n\nIf you want to iterate quickly while developing, it may sound a bit tedious to\nrestart Mopidy for every minor change. Then it's useful to have tests to\nexercise your code...\n\n\n.. _running-tests:\n\nRunning tests\n=============\n\nMopidy has quite good test coverage, and we would like all new code going into\nMopidy to come with tests.\n\n.. contents::\n   :local:\n\n\nTest it all\n-----------\n\nYou need to know at least one command; the one that runs all the tests::\n\n    tox\n\nThis will run exactly the same tests as our CI setup runs for all our\nbranches and pull requests. If this command turns green, you can be quite\nconfident that your pull request will get the green flag from CI as well,\nwhich is a requirement for it to be merged.\n\nAs this is the ultimate test command, it's also the one taking the most time to\nrun; up to a minute, depending on your system. But, if you have patience, this\nis all you need to know. Always run this command before pushing your changes to\nGitHub.\n\nIf you take a look at the tox config file, :file:`tox.ini`, you'll see that tox\nruns tests in multiple environments, including a ``ruff`` environment that\nlints the source code for issues and a ``docs`` environment that tests that the\ndocumentation can be built. You can also limit tox to just test specific\nenvironments using the ``-e`` option, e.g. to run just unit tests on Python 3.11::\n\n    tox -e py311\n\nTo learn more, see the `tox documentation <https://tox.readthedocs.io/>`_ .\n\nBefore submitting a pull request, we recommend running::\n\n    tox\n\nThis will locally run similar tests to what we use in our CI runs and help us to\nmerge high-quality contributions.\n\n\nRunning unit tests\n------------------\n\nUnder the hood, ``tox -e py311`` will use `pytest <https://docs.pytest.org/>`_\nas the test runner. We can also use it directly to run all tests::\n\n    pytest\n\npytest has lots of possibilities, so you'll have to dive into their docs and\nplugins to get full benefit from it. To get you interested, here are some\nexamples.\n\nWe can limit to just tests in a single directory to save time::\n\n    pytest tests/http/\n\nWith the help of the ``pytest-xdist`` plugin, we can run tests with four Python\nprocesses in parallel, which usually cuts the test time in half or more::\n\n    pytest -n 4\n\nAnother useful feature from ``pytest-xdist``, is the possibility to stop on the\nfirst test failure, watch the file system for changes, and then rerun the\ntests. This makes for a very quick code-test cycle::\n\n    pytest -f    # or --looponfail\n\nWith the help of the pytest-cov plugin, we can get a report on what parts of\nthe given module are covered by the test suite::\n\n    pytest --cov\n\n.. note::\n\n    Up to date test coverage statistics can also be viewed online at\n    `Codecov <https://codecov.io/gh/mopidy/mopidy>`_.\n\nIf we want to speed up the test suite, we can even get a list of the ten\nslowest tests::\n\n    pytest --durations=10\n\nBy now, you should be convinced that running pytest directly during\ndevelopment can be very useful.\n\n\nContinuous integration\n----------------------\n\nMopidy uses `GitHub Actions <https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy/actions>`_ for\nautomatically running the test suite when code is pushed to GitHub. This\nworks both for the main Mopidy repo, but also for any forks. This way, any\ncontributions to Mopidy through GitHub will automatically be tested, and the\nbuild status will be visible in the GitHub pull request interface, making it\neasier to evaluate the quality of pull requests.\n\nFor each successful build, the CI setup submits code coverage data to\n`Codecov`_. If you're out of work, Codecov might help you find areas in the\ncode which could need better test coverage.\n\n\n.. _code-linting:\n\nStyle checking and linting\n--------------------------\n\nWe're quite pedantic about :ref:`codestyle` and try hard to keep the Mopidy\ncode base a very clean and nice place to work in.\n\nLuckily, you can get very far by using the `ruff\n<https://github.com/astral-sh/ruff>`_ linter to check your code for issues before\nsubmitting a pull request. Mopidy's ruff rules are configured in :file:`pyproject.toml`.\nYou can either run the ``ruff`` tox environment, like our CI setup will do on\nyour pull request::\n\n    tox -e ruff\n\nOr you can run ruff directly::\n\n    ruff .\n\nIf successful, the command will not print anything at all.\n\n.. note::\n\n    In some rare cases it doesn't make sense to listen to ruff's warnings. In\n    those cases, ignore the check by appending ``# noqa: <warning code>`` to\n    the source line that triggers the warning. The ``# noqa`` part will make\n    ruff skip all checks on the line, while the warning code will help other\n    developers lookup what you are ignoring.\n\n\n.. _writing-docs:\n\nWriting documentation\n=====================\n\nTo write documentation, we use `Sphinx <https://www.sphinx-doc.org/>`_. See\ntheir site for lots of documentation on how to use Sphinx.\n\n.. note::\n\n    To generate a few graphs which are part of the documentation, you need to\n    install the graphviz package. You can install it from APT with::\n\n        sudo apt install graphviz\n\n    Other distributions typically use the same package name.\n\nTo build the documentation, go into the :file:`docs/` directory::\n\n    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/docs/\n\nThen, to see all available build targets, run::\n\n    make\n\nTo generate an HTML version of the documentation, run::\n\n    make html\n\nThe generated HTML will be available at :file:`_build/html/index.html`. To open\nit in a browser you can run either of the following commands, depending on your\nOS::\n\n    xdg-open _build/html/index.html    # Linux\n    open _build/html/index.html        # OS X\n\nThe documentation at https://docs.mopidy.com/ is hosted by `Read the Docs\n<https://readthedocs.org/>`_, which automatically updates the documentation\nwhen a change is pushed to the ``mopidy/mopidy`` repo at GitHub.\n\n\nWorking on extensions\n=====================\n\nMuch of the above also applies to Mopidy extensions, though they're often a bit\nsimpler. They don't have documentation sites and their test suites are either\nsmall and fast, or sadly missing entirely. Most of them use tox to run various\nlinters, and pytest can be used to run their test suites.\n\n.. contents::\n   :local:\n\n\nInstalling extensions\n---------------------\n\nAs always, the ``mopidy`` virtualenv should be active when working on\nextensions::\n\n    . ~/mopidy-dev/.venv/bin/activate\n\nJust like with non-development Mopidy installations, you can install extensions\nusing pip::\n\n    pip install Mopidy-Scrobbler\n\nInstalling an extension from its Git repo works the same way as with Mopidy\nitself. First, go to the Mopidy workspace::\n\n    cd ~/mopidy-dev/\n\nClone the desired Mopidy extension::\n\n    git clone https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy-spotify.git\n\nChange to the newly created extension directory::\n\n    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy-spotify/\n\nThen, install the extension in \"editable\" mode, so that it can be imported from\nanywhere inside the virtualenv and the extension is registered and discoverable\nthrough :mod:`importlib`::\n\n    pip install --editable .\n\nEvery extension will have a ``README.rst`` file. It may contain information\nabout extra dependencies required, development process, etc. Extensions usually\nhave a changelog in their GitHub releases page.\n\n\nUpgrading extensions\n--------------------\n\nExtensions often have a much quicker life cycle than Mopidy itself, often with\ndaily releases in periods of active development. To find outdated extensions in\nyour virtualenv, you can run::\n\n    pip list --outdated\n\nTo upgrade an extension installed with pip, simply use pip::\n\n    pip install --upgrade Mopidy-Scrobbler\n\nTo upgrade an extension installed from a Git repo, it's usually enough to pull\nthe new changes in::\n\n    cd ~/mopidy-dev/mopidy-spotify/\n    git pull\n\nOf course, if you have local modifications, you'll need to stash these away on\na branch or similar first.\n\nDepending on the changes to the extension, it may be necessary to update the\nmetadata about the extension package by installing it in \"editable\" mode\nagain::\n\n    pip install --editable .\n\n\nContribution workflow\n=====================\n\nBefore you being, make sure you've read the :ref:`contributing` page and the\nguidelines there. This section will focus more on the practical workflow.\n\nFor the examples, we're making a change to Mopidy. Approximately the same\nworkflow should work for most Mopidy extensions too.\n\n.. contents::\n   :local:\n\n\nSetting up Git remotes\n----------------------\n\nAssuming we already have a local Git clone of the upstream Git repo in\n:file:`~/mopidy-dev/mopidy/`, we can run ``git remote -v`` to list the\nconfigured remotes of the repo::\n\n    $ git remote -v\n    origin  https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (fetch)\n    origin  https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (push)\n\nFor clarity, we can rename the ``origin`` remote to ``upstream``::\n\n    $ git remote rename origin upstream\n    $ git remote -v\n    upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (fetch)\n    upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (push)\n\nIf you haven't already, `fork the repository\n<https://help.github.com/en/articles/fork-a-repo>`_ to your own GitHub account.\n\nThen, add the new fork as a remote to your local clone::\n\n    git remote add myuser git@github.com:myuser/mopidy.git\n\nThe end result is that you have both the upstream repo and your own fork as\nremotes::\n\n    $ git remote -v\n    myuser  git@github.com:myuser/mopidy.git (fetch)\n    myuser  git@github.com:myuser/mopidy.git (push)\n    upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (fetch)\n    upstream        https://github.com/mopidy/mopidy.git (push)\n\n\nCreating a branch\n-----------------\n\nFetch the latest data from all remotes without affecting your working\ndirectory::\n\n    git remote update --prune\n\nNow, we are ready to create and checkout a new branch off of the upstream\n``main`` branch for our work::\n\n    git checkout -b fix-crash-on-foo upstream/main\n\nDo the work, while remembering to adhere to code style, test the changes, make\nnecessary updates to the documentation, and making small commits with good\ncommit messages. All as described in :ref:`contributing` and elsewhere in\nthe :ref:`devenv` guide.\n\n\nCreating a pull request\n-----------------------\n\nWhen everything is done and committed, push the branch to your fork on GitHub::\n\n    git push myuser fix-crash-on-foo\n\nGo to the repository on GitHub where you want the change merged, in this case\nhttps://github.com/mopidy/mopidy, and `create a pull request\n<https://help.github.com/en/articles/creating-a-pull-request>`_.\n\n\nUpdating a pull request\n-----------------------\n\nWhen the pull request is created, our CI setup will run all tests on it.\nIf something fails, you'll usually get a notification from GitHub.\nYou might as well just fix the issues right away,\nas we won't merge a pull request without all CI builds being green.\nSee :ref:`running-tests` on how to run the same tests locally as\nour CI setup runs on your pull request.\n\nWhen you've fixed the issues, you can update the pull request simply by pushing\nmore commits to the same branch in your fork::\n\n    git push myuser fix-crash-on-foo\n\nLikewise, when you get review comments from other developers on your pull\nrequest, you're expected to create additional commits which addresses the\ncomments. Push them to your branch so that the pull request is updated.\n","numLines":550,"startLine":1,"totalLines":550}}}
